wiki_catalogs.name: Project Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the maya-platform-frontend project. Explain its purpose as a construction project management dashboard with secure authentication, object management, user roles, and reference data handling. Describe the high-level architecture using Vue 3, TypeScript, Pinia, and Vite. Highlight key features such as role-based access control, modular feature organization, and responsive UI components. Document the relationship between core modules (auth, objects, users, refs) and shared resources. Include setup prerequisites, technology choices, and deployment targets. Provide a conceptual overview suitable for new developers and technical leads. Illustrate with a system context diagram showing user interaction flow from login to feature usage.

wiki_catalogs.name: Component Hierarchy
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the component hierarchy of the maya-platform-frontend application. Explain how App.vue serves as the root component that orchestrates routing and global layout via Vue Router. Document the parent-child relationships between layout components (SidebarComponent, HeaderComponent) and feature-specific pages (ObjectsPage, UsersPage, CustomersPage). Illustrate how feature modules encapsulate their own sub-components (ObjectCard, UsersTable, CustomerModal) and integrate with shared components. Include diagrams showing the render tree from App.vue down to leaf components. Use actual code examples to demonstrate how props are passed from parent to child, how emits handle events, and how slots enable content projection. Address common patterns like conditional rendering of sidebar menus using menuItems.ts configuration and dynamic component loading through router views.

wiki_catalogs.name: Route Configuration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the route configuration system in the maya-platform-frontend application. Explain how Vue Router is initialized in routing.ts, including history mode (createWebHistory) usage and base path configuration. Document the structure of route objects: path, name, component (with lazy loading via dynamic imports), and meta fields such as required permissions and layout types. Illustrate how feature modules (auth, objects, refs, users) export their routes and are consolidated into the main router instance. Provide code examples showing route definitions for both public routes (e.g., login) and protected routes (e.g., ObjectsPage, UsersPage). Detail how nested routes are structured and how route names enable programmatic navigation. Include best practices for naming conventions and file organization.

wiki_catalogs.name: Authentication Store
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the authentication state management module using Pinia. Explain the structure of authStore including state properties like authenticated, user, and loading states. Document actions such as login, logout, and refreshToken, detailing their interaction with the authApi service. Describe getters like isAuthenticated and userRoles, and how they enable conditional rendering and access control. Illustrate how the store integrates with the authGuard to protect routes and manage session persistence. Include examples of error handling during authentication flows and token expiration strategies. Address store hydration on page reload and integration with localStorage/sessionStorage. Provide best practices for securing sensitive user data in the store and preventing XSS attacks.

wiki_catalogs.name: HTTP Client Configuration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create architectural documentation for the HTTP client implementation in the maya-platform-frontend application. Detail the Axios instance configuration in http.ts, including base URL, timeout, and default headers setup. Explain the centralized export through index.ts and how it enables consistent API calls across modules. Document the integration pattern with environment variables for different deployment targets. Provide examples of how components and stores import and use the HTTP client. Address best practices for request cancellation, timeout handling, and connection pooling. Include performance considerations such as connection reuse and payload compression.

wiki_catalogs.name: Object Data Model
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive data model documentation for the Object entity in the maya-platform-frontend application. Detail the ObjectsInterface including properties such as id, name, status, location, and timestamps. Document the ObjectStatus enum values (ACTIVE, ARCHIVED, PENDING, etc.) and their business lifecycle implications. Explain how the Object model relates to other entities like users and customers. Include examples of how this interface is used in components (ObjectCard, ObjectList) and stores (objectsStore). Illustrate with code snippets showing type enforcement, validation patterns, and API serialization. Provide guidance on extending the Object interface for new fields and maintaining backward compatibility.

wiki_catalogs.name: Authentication Module
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the authentication module of the maya-platform-frontend application. Explain the implementation of the login flow, token-based authentication, and route protection using the authGuard. Document the structure of the authStore in Pinia, including state properties like isAuthenticated and accessToken, actions for login/logout, and related mutations. Detail how auth.routes.ts defines public routes such as login and integrates with the main router. Describe the interaction between LoginPage.vue and the authApi service for credential submission. Include examples of how the authGuard intercepts navigation and redirects unauthenticated users. Address common issues such as token expiration handling, session persistence, and error states during login. Provide best practices for extending the module with features like MFA or social login.

wiki_catalogs.name: App.vue Root Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the App.vue root component in the maya-platform-frontend application. Explain how App.vue serves as the top-level component that initializes Vue Router and wraps the entire application layout. Document its role in rendering router views, managing global state access through Pinia, and providing consistent UI structure across all routes. Include examples showing how <router-view> dynamically loads feature pages (ObjectsPage, UsersPage, LoginPage) based on route configuration. Illustrate integration with core plugins like Pinia and Vue Router as initialized in main.ts. Address how global styles and theme settings from naiveTheme.ts are injected at this level. Provide guidance on extending App.vue for global error handling, loading states, or layout variations (e.g., authenticated vs unauthenticated views).

wiki_catalogs.name: Component Props Usage
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for component props usage in the maya-platform-frontend application. Explain how defineProps is used in ObjectCard.vue to declare type-safe properties for receiving object data from parent components like ObjectList.vue. Document the interface structure (e.g., ObjectInterface) imported from shared models and used in props definition. Illustrate how props are passed down to child components such as StatusTag.vue for rendering object status badges. Include examples showing prop validation, default values, and handling of optional properties. Address best practices followed in the codebase including one-way data flow, immutability of props, and using computed properties for transformations. Provide real code examples from ObjectCard.vue demonstrating the use of reactive props and their integration with template rendering.

wiki_catalogs.name: Authentication API Service
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive documentation for the Authentication API service module. Detail the exported functions including login and logout operations, their parameter signatures (credentials, tokens), and return types (authentication responses, error payloads). Document how this service interacts with the HTTP client to handle authentication endpoints, including header configuration and response interception. Explain token handling mechanisms and integration with the authStore for state synchronization. Provide concrete usage examples from LoginPage.vue and authStore.ts showing successful authentication flows and error handling patterns. Include information about request/response data structures, validation rules, and security considerations such as secure token storage and transmission.

wiki_catalogs.name: Sidebar Component

Include examples of how menu items are structured in menuItems.ts, including nested submenus, icon mapping via iconUtils.ts, and permission-based visibility. Address responsive behavior on mobile devices, including overlay mode and touch event handling. Detail accessibility features such as ARIA labels and keyboard navigation support.

Document how it subscribes to store changes and reacts to object status filters (active/archived). Illustrate integration with ObjectCard for item rendering, including event handling for object selection and navigation to ObjectDetailPage. Include examples of lifecycle hooks usage in <script setup>, route meta configuration, and permission-based UI rendering using permissions.enum.ts. wiki_catalogs.name: Object Management Components

Detail how ObjectCard.vue displays critical object information such as name, location, and status using StatusTag.vue with dynamic color mapping from mapping-status-object.ts based on object-status.enum.ts values. Document event handling patterns for card interactions, conditional rendering based on user permissions from permissions.enum.ts, and responsive design considerations. Include examples of how these components integrate with objectsStore.ts for state access and emit navigation events to ObjectDetailPage.vue.

wiki_catalogs.name: StatusTag Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the StatusTag.vue component in the maya-platform-frontend application. Document the component's props including 'status' (with type validation against ObjectStatus enum) and optional 'size' configurations. Illustrate how SCSS variables from variables.scss ensure consistent theming across the application. Provide examples of usage in ObjectCard.vue and ObjectsPage.vue where status tags are rendered for construction sites. Include details on accessibility attributes (ARIA labels), CSS class naming conventions, and extensibility for new status types. Address performance considerations with lightweight rendering and reactivity, and demonstrate how changes in object status are efficiently reflected in the UI through Vue’s reactivity system.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the LoadingOverlay.vue component in the maya-platform-frontend application. wiki_catalogs.name: Technology Stack & Dependencies
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the technology stack of the maya-platform-frontend application. wiki_catalogs.name: Props and State Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for props and state management in the maya-platform-frontend application. Thoroughly explain how component state is managed using Vue 3's reactive system and Composition API with <script setup> syntax. Document the use of defineProps and defineEmits for type-safe inter-component communication. Illustrate how local component state (e.g., form inputs in UserModal) is separated from global application state managed by Pinia stores. Provide concrete examples from ObjectCard.vue showing how object status is passed via props and rendered using StatusTag.vue. Explain best practices followed in the codebase such as one-way data flow, avoiding direct mutation of props, and using computed properties for derived state. Address common issues like prop drilling and how composables (e.g., useObjectsStore) mitigate this by providing centralized state access.

wiki_catalogs.name: Navigation Guards
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the navigation guard implementation in authGuard.ts. Explain how the beforeEach guard intercepts route transitions and verifies authentication state via the authStore. Document the logic flow: checking for required authentication, validating token presence, and redirecting unauthenticated users to the login page. Describe how meta fields on routes (e.g., requiresAuth) control guard behavior. Illustrate how the guard integrates with Pinia for reactive state access and handles asynchronous store initialization. Provide examples of both protected and public route handling, including edge cases like redirect loops. Include troubleshooting guidance for common issues such as guards not firing or incorrect redirect behavior. Highlight performance considerations and best practices for minimizing guard execution overhead.

wiki_catalogs.name: Theme Configuration

Detail the integration with Naive UI through naiveTheme.ts, where component-specific theme overrides are defined using TypeScript objects that align with Naive UI's theme specification. Describe how ui-naive.scss provides CSS-level overrides for fine-tuning component appearance that cannot be controlled via the theme object. Illustrate the dark mode implementation strategy using class-based switching and CSS variables. Provide concrete examples of how button styles or card backgrounds change based on the active theme. Include guidance on adding new theme tokens and synchronizing them between SCSS and Naive UI configurations. Address performance implications of theme switching and CSS bundle size considerations.

wiki_overview.content: # Comprehensive Analysis of vlk-group-frontend Project ## 1. Project Introduction The **vlk-group-frontend** project is a Vue 3-based frontend application built with Vite, designed as a modern web interface for managing construction objects, users, and reference data. The application follows a modular architecture with clear separation of concerns, leveraging TypeScript for type safety and Pinia for state management. ### Purpose Statement This application serves as a management dashboard for construction projects, allowing users to view, create, and manage objects (construction sites), customer references, and user roles. It provides a comprehensive interface for tracking project progress, team sizes, locations, and statuses across various regions in Russia. ### Core Goals and Objectives - Provide an intuitive UI for managing construction objects with detailed information - Implement secure authentication and role-based access control - Support multiple environments (development, staging, production) - Enable efficient data display with filtering, searching, and pagination capabilities - Maintain a consistent design system using Naive UI components ### Target Audience The primary users of this application are construction project managers, administrators, and team leads who need to monitor and manage multiple construction sites. The interface is designed for professionals who require quick access to project metrics, timelines, and team information. ## 2. Technical Architecture ### Component Breakdown The application follows a well-organized modular structure with the following key components: ```mermaid graph TD App[App Component] --> Router[Vue Router] App --> Pinia[Pinia Store] Router --> Auth[Auth Module] Router --> Main[Main Module] Router --> Objects[Objects Module] Router --> Users[Users Module] Router --> Refs[References Module] Main --> Sidebar[SidebarComponent] Objects --> ObjectsPage[ObjectsPage] Objects --> ObjectList[ObjectList] Objects --> ObjectCard[ObjectCard] Shared --> HeaderComponent[HeaderComponent] Shared --> StatusTag[StatusTag] Shared --> ConfirmDelete[ConfirmDelete] Shared --> API[Shared API Services] ``` ### Design Patterns The project implements several modern frontend design patterns: 1. **Modular Architecture**: The application is divided into distinct modules (auth, objects, users, refs) with their own routing, components, pages, and stores. 2. **Composition API**: Vue 3's Composition API is used extensively with `setup` syntax in Vue components. 3. **State Management**: Pinia is used for centralized state management with dedicated stores for each module. 4. **Dependency Injection**: Services are injected using composables (e.g., `useAuthApi`, `useObjectsStore`). 5. **Interceptor Pattern**: HTTP request/response interceptors handle authentication and error handling globally. ### System Relationships ```mermaid graph TD A[User Interface] --> B[Vue Components] B --> C[Pinia Stores] C --> D[API Services] D --> E[HTTP Client] E --> F[Backend API] G[Router] --> H[Route Guards] H --> C E --> I[Interceptors] I --> J[Token Refresh] J --> K[Local Storage] ``` ### Data Flow ```mermaid flowchart TD A[User Interaction] --> B[Vue Component] B --> C[Pinia Action] C --> D[API Service Call] D --> E[HTTP Client with Interceptors] E --> F[Backend API] F --> G[Response] G --> H[Response Interceptor] H --> I[Error/Token Handling] I --> J[Pinia State Update] J --> K[Component Re-render] ``` ## 3. Implementation Details ### Main Entry Points The application bootstraps through `main.ts`, which initializes the Vue app, registers Pinia for state management, and configures the router. ```typescript import './styles/main.scss' import App from '@/root/App.vue' import router from '@/root/routing' import { createApp } from 'vue' import { createPinia } from 'pinia' const app = createApp(App) app.use(createPinia()) app.use(router) app.mount('#app') ``` Sources: - [main.ts](/Users/euegne/work/projects/home/maya-platform/maya-platform-frontend/src/main.ts#L1-L14) ### Core Modules #### Authentication Module The authentication system is comprehensive, handling login, logout, token refresh, and route protection. **Auth Store Implementation:** ```typescript export const useAuthStore = defineStore('auth', (): AuthState & AuthActions => { const accessToken = ref(null) const refreshTokenValue = ref(null) const isAuthenticated = ref(false) const login = async (email: string, password: string) => { try { isLoading.value = true error.value = null const response = await authApi.login({ email, password }) accessToken.value = response.access refreshTokenValue.value = response.refresh isAuthenticated.value = true localStorage.setItem('accessToken', response.access) localStorage.setItem('refreshToken', response.refresh) router.push('/objects') } catch (err: unknown) { const errorMessage = err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Ошибка входа' error.value = errorMessage throw err } finally { isLoading.value = false } } // ... other methods }) ``` Sources: - [authStore.ts](/Users/euegne/work/projects/home/maya-platform/maya-platform-frontend/src/root/auth/store/authStore.ts#L1-L114) #### HTTP Client Configuration The HTTP client is configured with interceptors for request modification and authentication handling. ```typescript export function createHttpClient() { const http = axios.create({ baseURL: currentConfig.apiBaseUrl, withCredentials: true, maxRedirects: 3, paramsSerializer: { serialize: (params) => { const searchParams = new URLSearchParams() Object.entries(params).forEach(([key, value]) => { if (value === undefined || value === null) return if (Array.isArray(value)) { value.forEach((item) => searchParams.append(key, String(item))) } else { searchParams.append(key, String(value)) } }) return searchParams.toString() }, }, }) // REQUEST INTERCEPTOR http.interceptors.request.use(createRequestInterceptor(), (error) => Promise.reject(error)) // RESPONSE INTERCEPTOR http.interceptors.response.use((response: AxiosResponse) => response, createAuthInterceptor(http)) return http } ``` Sources: - [http.ts](/Users/euegne/work/projects/home/maya-platform/maya-platform-frontend/src/root/core/api/http.ts#L1-L40) ### Configuration Approach The project uses environment-specific configuration files and Vite's mode system to manage different deployment environments. **Environment Configuration:** ```typescript // Example from development.ts export const currentConfig = { apiBaseUrl: 'https://vlk-g.dev.api.thelightech.com/backend/api', // ... other config } ``` **Vite Configuration:** ```typescript export default defineConfig(() => { return { plugins: [ vue(), vueDevTools(), svgLoader(), Components({ resolvers: [NaiveUiResolver()], }), ], resolve: { alias: { '@': fileURLToPath(new URL('./src', import.meta.url)), '@core': fileURLToPath(new URL('./src/root/core', import.meta.url)), // ... other aliases }, }, server: { proxy: { '/backend/api': { target: 'https://vlk-g.dev.api.thelightech.com', changeOrigin: true, secure: true, rewrite: (path) => path, }, }, }, } }) ``` Sources: - [vite.config.ts](/Users/euegne/work/projects/home/maya-platform/maya-platform-frontend/vite.config.ts#L1-L44) ### External Dependencies The project leverages several key dependencies: ```json "dependencies": { "@types/axios": "^0.9.36", "@vueuse/core": "^13.8.0", "axios": "^1.11.0", "naive-ui": "^2.42.0", "pinia": "^3.0.3", "vue": "^3.5.18", "vue-router": "^4.5.1" } ``` **Integration Example - Naive UI with Auto-import:** ```typescript // vite.config.ts import Components from 'unplugin-vue-components/vite' import { NaiveUiResolver } from 'unplugin-vue-components/resolvers' export default defineConfig(() => { return { plugins: [ // ... other plugins Components({ resolvers: [NaiveUiResolver()], }), ], } }) ``` Sources: - [package.json](/Users/euegne/work/projects/home/maya-platform/maya-platform-frontend/package.json#L1-L61) - [vite.config.ts](/Users/euegne/work/projects/home/maya-platform/maya-platform-frontend/vite.config.ts#L1-L44) ### Component Relationship Diagrams ```mermaid graph LR App[App.vue] --> Router[vue-router] Router --> AuthModule[Auth Module] Router --> ObjectsModule[Objects Module] Router --> UsersModule[Users Module] Router --> RefsModule[References Module] AuthModule --> AuthStore[authStore.ts] AuthModule --> AuthApi[authApi.ts] AuthModule --> AuthGuard[authGuard.ts] ObjectsModule --> ObjectsStore[objectsStore.ts] ObjectsModule --> ObjectsPage[ObjectsPage.vue] ObjectsModule --> ObjectList[ObjectList.vue] ObjectsModule --> ObjectCard[ObjectCard.vue] ObjectsPage --> ObjectList ObjectList --> ObjectCard ObjectCard --> StatusTag[StatusTag.vue] Shared --> HeaderComponent[HeaderComponent.vue] Shared --> SearchComponent[SearchComponent.vue] Shared --> ConfirmDelete[ConfirmDelete.vue] ObjectsPage --> HeaderComponent ObjectsPage --> SearchComponent ``` ## 4. wiki_readme.content:
# vlk-group-frontend

This template should help get you started developing with Vue 3 in Vite.

## Recommended IDE Setup

[VSCode](https://code.visualstudio.com/) + [Volar](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=Vue.volar) (and disable Vetur).

## Type Support for `.vue` Imports in TS

TypeScript cannot handle type information for `.vue` imports by default, so we replace the `tsc` CLI with `vue-tsc` for type checking. In editors, we need [Volar](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=Vue.volar) to make the TypeScript language service aware of `.vue` types.

## Customize configuration

See [Vite Configuration Reference](https://vite.dev/config/).

## Project Setup

```sh
npm install
```

### Compile and Hot-Reload for Development

```sh
npm run dev
```

### Type-Check, Compile and Minify for Production

```sh
npm run build
```

### Lint with [ESLint](https://eslint.org/)

```sh
npm run lint
```
